In the field of software engineering continuous integration (CI) and continuous delivery (CD) are the essential 
practices for developing and delivering software efficiently and reliably.
CI involves regularly integrating code changes into a shared repository, allowing developers to detect and 
address issues early on. 
CD, on the other hand, extends CI by automating the deployment process, enabling frequent and seamleass releases of software

To achieve successful CI/CD, teams employ various tools and technique. One widely used tool is JENKINS,  an open source
automation server that supports the entire CI/CD pipeline. It provides functionalities such as building, testing, and 
deploying applications, all while ensuring code quality and version control.

Another Key technique used in CI/CD is containerization, which involves encapsulating an application and its dependencies
into isolated contan=iners. Docker is an popular platform for containerization, allowing developers to package their 
application in a poratable and consistent format. Containers facilitate faster and more efficient development, testing 
and deployment processes.

In addition to tools and techniques, CI/CD relies on effective collaboration and communication within development teams.
Agile methodologies, such as Scrum and Kanban, promote iterative development and close collaboration between development
